Intuition
This problem is a direct extension of the in-place linked list reversal pattern. The main challenge is determining whether a complete group of k nodes exists before attempting a reversal. To handle this, we use a checker pointer that tries to move k steps ahead from the node before the current group. If it cannot complete all k moves, there are not enough nodes remaining and we leave the rest of the list unchanged. Otherwise, a valid group exists, and we reverse exactly k nodes using the standard linked list reversal technique. After reversing the group, we reconnect it to the remaining list and continue processing the next group.

Approach
Create a dummy node pointing to the head and initialize a pointer prev to the dummy node. prev will always point to the node before the current group.

Before reversing a group, use a checker pointer starting from prev and move it k times:

If checker cannot complete all k moves, there are fewer than k nodes remaining, so return dummy.next.
Otherwise, a valid group of size k exists.

Store the start of the current group in group_start = prev.next. This node will become the tail of the reversed group after reversal.
Reverse exactly k nodes using the standard in-place linked list reversal pattern:
curr traverses the group.
helper stores the head of the partially reversed segment.
After reversing:
helper points to the head of the reversed group.
curr points to the first node after the group.
group_start becomes the tail of the reversed group.
Reconnect the reversed group:
Connect prev to the new head of the reversed group.
Connect the tail of the reversed group (group_start) to curr.
Move prev to group_start and repeat the process for the next group.
Continue until fewer than k nodes remain.

Complexity
Time Complexity:
O(n)
Each node is visited a constant number of times. The checker pointer is used to verify whether a group of k nodes exists, and the reversal loop processes each node once within its group. Therefore, the total work done across the entire list is linear in the number of nodes.

Space Complexity:
O(1)
The reversal is performed in-place using a constant number of pointers (prev, checker, curr, helper, and group_start), so no extra space proportional to the input size is used.

Code
# Definition for singly-linked list.
# class ListNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.next = next
class Solution:
    def reverseKGroup(self, head: Optional[ListNode], k: int) -> Optional[ListNode]:
        dummy = ListNode(0,head)
        prev = dummy
        
        while True:
            checker = prev
            for _ in range(k):
                if checker.next == None:
                    return dummy.next
                checker = checker.next
            group_start = prev.next
            curr = group_start
            helper = None

            #reversing the nodes
            for _ in range(k):
                new = curr.next
                curr.next = helper
                helper = curr
                curr = new

            #rejoing nodes
            prev.next = helper
            group_start.next = curr

            #moving prev
            prev = group_start
